opendcl-renderer-scaffold — Qt6 subprocess for OpenDCL
======================================================

See also: opendcl.plan, opendcl-wire-protocol.issue,
opendcl-runtime-core.issue, opendcl-controls.issue.

Context
-------

The DCL Qt renderer
(`clautolisp/tools/clautolisp-gui-qt/`) is a clean reference for the
subprocess pattern: stdio s-expr framing, dialog lifecycle,
widget-key dispatch. For OpenDCL we need a renderer that speaks the
extended protocol from opendcl-wire-protocol.issue and materialises
a much richer widget set.

Decision: *extend the existing renderer*. Multiplex DCL and OpenDCL
in the same binary, gated by the `:opendcl-hello` handshake. Rename
nothing; the binary's *capability* — not its name — distinguishes
the two surfaces. This avoids two near-duplicate Qt codebases and
keeps the `--gui` flag and `CLAUTOLISP_GUI` env discovery unchanged.

In scope (V1 — just enough to land the Phase 1 vertical slice)
---------------------------------------------------------------

  1. Protocol handshake.
       - On startup announce `(:opendcl-hello 1 (:button :edit
         :label :ok :cancel))`.
       - Receive `:project-load` and stash the canonical project
         tree in a per-PID map.
       - Receive `:form-show` and instantiate a QDialog (modal) or
         a QDockWidget (palette).

  2. Initial widget catalogue:
       - Label  ↔ QLabel
       - Button ↔ QPushButton
       - EditBox ↔ QLineEdit
       - OK/Cancel ↔ QDialogButtonBox

  3. Property get/set roundtrip:
       - `(:request RID :get-property FID CID NAME)` reads the
         widget's property by mapped name (e.g. "Text" → `text()`),
         emits `(:reply RID (:ok VALUE))`.
       - `(:property-set FID CID NAME VALUE)` updates the widget
         property; one-way, no reply.
       - Mapping table lives in
         `tools/clautolisp-gui-qt/source/opendcl_property_map.{hpp,cpp}`.

  4. Event emission:
       - `clicked` → `(:opendcl-event FID CID :click)`
       - `editingFinished` → `(:opendcl-event FID CID :focus-lost)`
       - `textChanged` → `(:opendcl-event FID CID :property-changed
                          "Text" OLD NEW)`

  5. CMake updates: new sources added to the existing
     `clautolisp-gui-qt` target. No new binary.

  6. Smoke test: a hand-written sexp wire trace driving the
     renderer through `cat trace.sexp | clautolisp-gui-qt --replay`
     (a debug-only flag) should bring up the form, take a synthetic
     click, and exit cleanly. Captured as a Makefile target so CI
     can ssh into an Xvfb session and run it.

Out of scope
------------

  - The advanced widget catalogue (TreeView, ListView with columns,
    PropertyGrid, ImageList, DateTimePicker, RichEdit, dockable
    palette tab stacks). Captured in `opendcl-controls.issue`.
  - Designer-mode editing.
  - Native-Windows renderer for parity with real OpenDCL — defer.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - The existing `clautolisp-gui-qt` binary still passes all DCL
    regression scenarios; no break in the DCL path.
  - With the runtime-core builtins, running an end-to-end
    "show a form with one Button and one EditBox, click the button"
    flow works under Xvfb (and locally on a developer machine) and
    produces the expected wire trace.
  - Replay smoke test is wired into `make test` (gated by Xvfb
    availability — skip cleanly if no display is reachable).

Notes
-----

Keep widget *identity* on the C++ side keyed by `(FID, CID)`; do not
try to recreate AutoLISP symbol identity in the renderer. The runtime
owns the source of truth and is responsible for translating user
events back to the right `defun`.

The replay flag (`--replay FILE`) is worth keeping as a permanent
debug aid; it costs nothing and pays back the first time a
production scenario regresses.
